When you declare this:
```rust
trait HasAssoc {
    type Assoc;
    fn tap(some: Self::Assoc) -> Self::Assoc;
}
impl HasAssoc for i32 {
    type Assoc = &'a i32;

    fn tap(some: Self::Assoc) -> Self::Assoc {
        some
    }
}
```
you get this error:
```
error[E0261]: use of undeclared lifetime name `'a`
  --> src\main.rs:12:19
   |
12 |     type Assoc = &'a i32;
   |                   ^^ undeclared lifetime
   |
help: consider introducing lifetime `'a` here
   |
11 | impl<'a> HasAssoc for i32 {

```
but if you follow the suggestion and place the lifetime parameter on the impl block, you get this:

```rust
error[E0207]: the lifetime parameter `'a` is not constrained by the impl trait, self type, or predicates
  --> src\main.rs:11:6
   |
11 | impl<'a> HasAssoc for i32 {
   |      ^^ unconstrained lifetime parameter
```

Until today, I thought this requires GATs and I wanted to suggest to put this information in the error message (which some other errors already tells you). But after playing around, I am actually not sure if it requires GATs or if it's even possible - either way, I don't know how to fix the error, so I think the diagnostics could be improved 😉
